00:46.900 --> 00:51.300
Of all the themes handled by science fiction authors, that of alien contact has been one

00:51.300 --> 00:53.420
of the most consistently popular and fascinating.

00:53.900 --> 00:54.820
For a good reason too.

00:55.500 --> 00:59.900
Aliens, whether they be the hostile bug-eyed monsters of the old pulp magazines or the friendly

00:59.900 --> 01:03.680
creatures of close encounters of the third kind, have always been one of the biggest

01:03.680 --> 01:05.000
attractions of science fiction.

01:05.580 --> 01:10.260
In the past, stories of alien contact were usually written as thrillers, with the sole

01:10.260 --> 01:12.320
and simple intention of scaring readers.

01:13.020 --> 01:17.840
HD Wells, The War of the Worlds, is probably the best example of that type of story.

01:18.160 --> 01:18.960
But that's changed.

01:19.800 --> 01:24.040
Many contemporary writers have provided more thoughtful treatments of aliens, deepening

01:24.040 --> 01:27.300
the realism and the significance of narratives of alien contact.

01:35.540 --> 01:40.440
Of course, before you can have a story of alien contact, you have to have some aliens.

01:41.080 --> 01:45.020
One of the most provocative descriptions of aliens in all of science fiction is found

01:45.020 --> 01:48.560
in Larry Nivens and Jerry Pornell's The Moat in God's Eye.

01:49.060 --> 01:53.800
The success of that book is largely due to the unique and ingenious aliens, the Moaties,

01:54.040 --> 01:55.540
that Niven created for the story.

01:55.980 --> 02:00.180
It's interesting though, that Niven says he doesn't really create aliens for a story,

02:00.560 --> 02:02.460
but suggests that it's the other way around.

02:03.340 --> 02:07.200
I always design aliens for themselves.

02:07.600 --> 02:11.780
I almost never design an alien to match a story.

02:12.420 --> 02:17.280
The story, some story, will eventually include the alien.

02:17.600 --> 02:19.320
The alien stands for itself.

02:20.020 --> 02:24.520
There are two particularly fascinating things that Niven incorporated into these Moaties.

02:25.040 --> 02:26.760
One is the fact that they are not symmetrical.

02:27.450 --> 02:32.380
They have a head, torso, legs and arms, as humans do, but the arms are disproportionate.

02:32.800 --> 02:35.100
One is small and thin, the other is large and powerful.

02:35.480 --> 02:35.760
Right.

02:36.160 --> 02:40.260
Niven says he took that idea from studying the structures of living creatures on Earth.

02:41.000 --> 02:49.980
In that case, I had the idea that I was following a progression with a protozoan, with an amoeba.

02:50.530 --> 02:53.680
You get radial symmetry inside and out.

02:54.960 --> 03:03.460
Move up a goodly distance and you find starfishes with radial symmetry on the outside and bilateral symmetry on the inside.

03:03.680 --> 03:08.840
Move up a little further, you find flat worms and worms of all stance.

03:10.020 --> 03:14.100
At the level of bilateral symmetry inside and out.

03:14.600 --> 03:24.980
The goal is as far as a human, you find bilateral symmetry on the outside and no symmetry, well, half symmetrical on the inside.

03:25.380 --> 03:28.600
The lungs look symmetrical, the kidneys look symmetrical.

03:29.260 --> 03:32.620
The intestines look like somebody dropped a plate of spaghetti.

03:33.080 --> 03:35.620
I tried to move on to the next step.

03:39.220 --> 03:41.780
Bilaterally unsymmetrical on the outside.

03:41.780 --> 03:46.720
And I got the original Modi, which was the engineer for us.

03:58.220 --> 04:02.840
The other ingenious idea Niven developed for the Modi's is the way they construct and use machines.

04:03.620 --> 04:09.320
They're highly skilled tool users, but they have no standard pre-manufactured machines, parts or tools.

04:09.320 --> 04:13.920
They simply alter or reshape whatever they find around them at the time to suit their needs.

04:14.460 --> 04:17.140
Niven says that particular idea just came to him.

04:17.520 --> 04:19.460
It seemed interesting and even logical.

04:20.200 --> 04:25.760
I was just playing with the ideas at that point and that one seemed like a fun one.

04:26.300 --> 04:37.140
It also seemed likely enough if you've got a critter with not much intelligence except in the direction of tool making and tool altering.

04:38.260 --> 04:39.660
Then why not?

04:40.740 --> 04:45.800
The thing has to keep testing its ability or it will lose it.

04:46.400 --> 04:51.280
It might as well be designing something every time it needs a specific machine.

04:52.300 --> 05:00.040
Besides the ingenuity Niven demonstrated in creating the Modi's, he and Pornell also weaved some unexpected twists into the first contact theme.

05:00.860 --> 05:04.060
Our reader interested in aliens are more specifically in first contact.

05:04.460 --> 05:06.580
Can't afford to overlook the Moten Gautzai.

