06:42.740 --> 06:48.780
The so-called New Wave in Science Fiction, which began in the mid-60s, was simply a new way of writing traditional science fiction.

06:48.780 --> 06:53.920
There were changes, for instance, in style, and characterization was given more emphasis.

06:54.580 --> 06:59.400
And the New Wave treated themes such as sex and religion that science fiction hadn't really touched before.

06:59.860 --> 07:07.440
In general, the New Wave changed the stereotype science fiction formulas that had been around since the pulp days of the 20s, 30s, and 40s.

07:07.580 --> 07:13.720
Frederick Poll, who's been an author, an editor, and an agent in the field of science fiction, has something to say about that change.

07:13.720 --> 07:24.500
The New Wave was an attempt, I guess, 15 years ago or more of a number of writers to break away from the traditional kinds of science fiction.

07:24.800 --> 07:27.180
In fact, most of them didn't want to call it science fiction anymore.

07:27.560 --> 07:31.140
They wanted to call it speculative fiction or call it nothing at all.

07:31.880 --> 07:39.920
And they were interested primarily in writing about inner space rather than outer space, and secondarily a lot of them.

07:39.920 --> 07:44.120
Things like the drug culture and rock music and so on.

07:44.900 --> 07:54.260
But in the rather bitter internal struggle that went on in science fiction, a lot of people taking sides one way or the other.

07:54.780 --> 07:56.680
I think everyone was deeply affected.

08:05.680 --> 08:12.360
But we need to remember here that the New Wave wasn't really a planned and deliberate movement by a unified group of writers.

08:12.900 --> 08:20.160
One of the principal proponents of the New Wave, author Norman Spinrad, believes it was just a bunch of diverse writers doing their own thing.

08:20.160 --> 08:26.020
There was an old wave, but there was never as a coherent philosophy in school of science fiction.

08:26.040 --> 08:30.080
But there was never a New Wave in the same sense. There were a lot of waves.

08:30.240 --> 08:32.280
There were a lot of different people doing a lot of different things.

08:33.080 --> 08:35.840
The people that were identified as New Wave were very diverse.

08:36.560 --> 08:45.640
What I was actually writing was very different to what Tom Dish was writing, or Boulard, or Zalazny, Delaney, were also identified as New Wave writers.

08:45.640 --> 08:53.880
This stuff is much more Zalazny and Delaney and myself and Boulard and all this and Mike.

08:55.320 --> 09:03.540
There were more differences between our work than between our work taking us to totality and the old stuff.

09:04.040 --> 09:08.700
There was more difference within the so-called New Wave than there was within the so-called Old Wave.

09:09.480 --> 09:13.900
But Spinrad also thinks the New Wave was tightly connected to what was happening in society.

09:14.880 --> 09:23.760
And of course this mirrored the cultural climate at the time. It mirrored what was happening politically, it mirrored what was happening in music, it mirrored what was happening in movies.

09:24.120 --> 09:28.400
It was a phenomenon that went through the West and civilization as a whole.

09:35.200 --> 09:37.560
There are those who say the New Wave is dead.

09:38.060 --> 09:43.040
Five-time Hugo winner Larry Nivens says so, for instance, and offers a reason for his passing.

09:43.040 --> 09:51.900
The New Wave is a very persuasive thing and very easy to use to justify bad stories.

09:53.360 --> 09:54.640
I think that's what killed it.

09:55.140 --> 10:07.380
Not that increased characterization and experiments with typography and story format are a bad thing in themselves.

10:07.380 --> 10:13.920
It's so easy to use New Wave to justify a bad story. It was bound to collapse.

10:20.160 --> 10:24.580
The influence of the New Wave is still around, though. It's left its mark on the field.

10:25.080 --> 10:28.500
Science fiction has been broadened, maybe enhanced somehow because of it.

10:28.940 --> 10:30.260
Frederick Paul states it well.

10:31.420 --> 10:39.600
And the New Wave, if nothing else, taught a bunch of old dinosaurs like Asimov and Pine Line and Meeth.

10:39.860 --> 10:43.160
But there were non-traditional ways of constructing a novel.

10:43.640 --> 10:51.520
See, most of us had grown up when science fiction was in the pulp magazines, and most of it was written according to some variant of a pulp formula.

10:52.180 --> 10:58.140
It turned out that wasn't necessary. And I think the New Wave is responsible for teaching us that.

