12:33.160 --> 12:36.380
The award-winning novel Ringworld is probably Larry Niven's finest work.

12:36.980 --> 12:43.600
The Ringworld is an immense ring, large enough to hold 3 million Earths, and with a thousand mile high wall to hold in its atmosphere.

12:44.120 --> 12:45.620
It also has continents and oceans.

12:46.340 --> 12:51.520
The Ringworld contains trillions of inhabitants of different species and derives energy from the sun at its center.

12:52.120 --> 12:55.440
Niven recalls where he obtained the idea for such a fantastic structure.

12:56.240 --> 13:00.200
I ran across the concept basin sphere.

13:01.400 --> 13:08.080
Dyson the mathematician came up with the concept basin shell and he was misunderstood to some extent.

13:08.540 --> 13:12.760
So presently I ran across an article about basin spheres.

13:13.480 --> 13:20.240
A picture that is a golf ball 93 million miles in radius with a sun at the center.

13:20.240 --> 13:26.080
And gravity generators all around the outside so he would live on the inside.

13:26.320 --> 13:31.180
Terraform it with oceans and soil and air.

13:32.800 --> 13:35.520
I ran across that and I didn't like it.

13:35.640 --> 13:36.880
I thought it could be improved.

13:37.600 --> 13:39.340
And I wound up with the Ringworld.

13:46.520 --> 13:52.660
Ritter studied the science behind the Ringworld and wrote Niven about seeming inconsistencies in the design of the immense artifact.

13:53.880 --> 13:58.900
Column errors and elaborations because some of them don't really fit the errors.

13:59.160 --> 14:02.540
It's just something that hadn't gotten into the original book.

14:03.240 --> 14:05.960
One of the errors was spotted by some MIT students.

14:05.960 --> 14:08.320
It had to do with the instability of the Ringworld.

14:35.960 --> 14:37.700
The Ringworld is unstable.

14:38.120 --> 14:39.420
The Ringworld is unstable.

14:41.600 --> 14:48.460
It still took about seven years for anyone to figure out the exact numbers for the instability.

14:48.800 --> 14:49.860
And they are horrifying.

14:50.180 --> 14:57.820
The Ringworld a major solar flare would have the Ringworld grinding against its sun in five years.

14:59.220 --> 15:00.960
Well I worked it into a plot.

15:01.600 --> 15:04.520
That was one elaboration or error.

15:05.220 --> 15:09.200
Even teenage readers analyzed his Ringworld with a critical scientific eye.

15:09.960 --> 15:13.460
A high school class in Florida got to work on the Ringworld.

15:14.180 --> 15:22.200
And their conclusion was that the Ringworld's worst problem is that all the top soil would wind up in the oceans in about 3,000 years.

15:22.880 --> 15:25.160
There are no earthquakes on the Ringworld.

15:25.620 --> 15:27.460
No mountain building forces.

15:34.780 --> 15:39.960
But in a sequel, Ringworld engineers, Niven attempted to correct such deficiencies.

15:40.420 --> 15:43.600
He devised a way to answer the criticism of the Florida high schoolers.

15:45.780 --> 15:47.380
Okay, that's a tough one.

15:47.520 --> 15:58.120
I set up a spill pipe system that runs the bottom from the sea bottoms under the Ringworld and up over the edge of the Ringworld.

16:00.000 --> 16:09.940
That even allows you some, uh, some mines accumulation of useful metals.

16:20.120 --> 16:23.460
Fan response of that sort caused Ringworld engineers to be written.

16:23.460 --> 16:30.720
And although Niven once said he wouldn't write anymore in the Known Space series, the body of stories to which Ringworld belongs, he's not so sure anymore.

16:32.240 --> 16:37.640
I've given up saying that the, uh, that the Known Space series is daily.

16:38.360 --> 16:39.840
There's just no point in it.

16:39.960 --> 16:44.440
I've written five books worth of Known Space stories since I said that.

